text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!TypologyOfPhoneticContrasts]]%0a%0a!Tone Systems: Comparing English and Mandarin%0a%0a:Author: BenP%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aI consider the similarities between intonation and tone and question how they developed.%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aA tonal language is one which contains words that are only distinguished by the tone of pronunciation. The same collection of letters in a tonal language can mean two different words depending on how the speaker emphasizes the syllables. Mandarin is one example of a tonal language, while English is not.%0a%0aAs an English speaker and not a Mandarin speaker, I find that it would be difficult to learn Mandarin because regulating tone for individual syllables would be hard for me. I am more used to navigating intonation, which can change the meaning of sentences rather than words. For example, in class, we looked at the example, "GIOVANNI said that Olga went to the store" vs "Giovanni said that OLGA went to the store" (I'm using caps for italics). In this example, its clear that the important information, such as the answer to the question of "Who said that Olga went to the store?" or "Who went to the store?" is emphasized. Still, it is possible to convey the same information, only less dramatically, without changing intonation.%0a%0aIt seems to me that intonation and tone are related in this way. Meaning is emphasized and conveyed, respectively, by the sound of the speaker. Tone seems like a continuation of intonation in this way. In considering how languages develop, I wonder whether intonation progressed into tone systems in tonal languages, intonation developed from tone, or if the two progressed independently of each other.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210227-173318-362970#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Learning tones for non-native Mandarin speakers %0a-> - david_h%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aStudies have shown that one of the greatest difficulties of English speakers learning Mandarin is the tonal system. Since English does not have a tonal system that dictates lexical differences, intentionally producing pitch changes and contours where they are needed is often inconsistent and error-prone.%0a%0aOne linguist Chao Yuan-ren helped people to better understand how Mandarin tones should sound like by assigning each tone to a musical scale equivalent. This helps solve the problem of non-native Mandarin speakers from using incorrect pitch and/or contours when speaking Mandarin.%0a%0aAn interesting observation mentioned in the study is that some tones are harder for native speakers of non-tonal languages to learn. The easiest to learn was T1 (high level), then T4 (falling stressing), followed by T2 (rising) and T3 (falling and rising) respectively.%0a%0aSource:%0a%0aShi, Hui, "A Method of Teaching English Speaking Learners to Produce Mandarin-Chinese Tones" (2018).%0aGraduate Theses, Dissertations, and Problem Reports. 6633.%0ahttps://researchrepository.wvu.edu/etd/6633%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210227-173318-362970#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: :)%0a(:Category: TypologyOfPhoneticContrasts:)
