diff:1614447198:1613863925:=49,67c49%0a%3c #foxbegin 210227-173318-362970#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Learning tones for non-native Mandarin speakers %0a%3c -> - david_h%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c Studies have shown that one of the greatest difficulties of English speakers learning Mandarin is the tonal system. Since English does not have a tonal system that dictates lexical differences, intentionally producing pitch changes and contours where they are needed is often inconsistent and error-prone.%0a%3c %0a%3c One linguist Chao Yuan-ren helped people to better understand how Mandarin tones should sound like by assigning each tone to a musical scale equivalent. This helps solve the problem of non-native Mandarin speakers from using incorrect pitch and/or contours when speaking Mandarin.%0a%3c %0a%3c An interesting observation mentioned in the study is that some tones are harder for native speakers of non-tonal languages to learn. The easiest to learn was T1 (high level), then T4 (falling stressing), followed by T2 (rising) and T3 (falling and rising) respectively.%0a%3c %0a%3c Source:%0a%3c %0a%3c Shi, Hui, "A Method of Teaching English Speaking Learners to Produce Mandarin-Chinese Tones" (2018).%0a%3c Graduate Theses, Dissertations, and Problem Reports. 6633.%0a%3c https://researchrepository.wvu.edu/etd/6633%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210227-173318-362970#%0a---%0a> %0a
